    seo_title: 'What is Doeskin? | William Ashford',
    seo_description: 'Doeskin is a finely milled, densely woven wool with a smooth, velvety face. Discover why it is prized for ceremonial and formal British tailoring.',
    short_definition: 'Doeskin is a tightly woven, heavily milled wool cloth with an exceptionally smooth, close-cut nap that resembles the soft skin of a doe. It is one of the most refined face-finished wools produced in Britain, long associated with formal uniforms, ceremonial dress, and fine tailoring.',
    full_definition: `Doeskin takes its name from its resemblance to the soft, smooth inner surface of a doe's skin — a comparison that speaks directly to its defining quality: an almost velvet-like surface that is flat, dense, and extraordinarily fine to the touch. It is woven in a twill structure, typically a five-shaft satin twill, which creates a smooth diagonal foundation before the cloth undergoes an intensive finishing process involving heavy milling, cropping, and raising to produce its characteristic face.

The production of doeskin cloth is a speciality of the fine English wool-milling tradition, centred historically on the West of England — particularly Gloucestershire and Wiltshire — where the soft local water was ideally suited to the fulling and finishing processes. After weaving, the cloth is milled until the fibres interlock tightly, then the surface is carefully raised and sheared back to leave an immaculate, near-seamless face. The resulting cloth is dense, substantial, and almost impervious to the elements.

In menswear, doeskin occupies a distinguished niche. It has been the standard cloth for military officer dress uniforms and ceremonial coats for several centuries, and this heritage lends it an air of authority and formality. In civil tailoring, a doeskin overcoat or a doeskin waistcoat cut for morning dress represents some of the finest and most considered choices a man can make. The smooth, lustrous face of the cloth is exceptionally elegant in dark navy, charcoal, or black, and it holds the crease and silhouette of a garment with remarkable precision.

The wearing qualities of doeskin are well suited to formal occasions. The cloth does not wrinkle easily, sheds light rain with its dense face, and maintains its immaculate appearance across a long day. It is not the most breathable of cloths, which aligns it firmly with cooler months. Properly cared for, a doeskin garment ages slowly and gracefully, its face growing ever smoother with gentle use.`,
    properties: 'Fibre type: Pure wool (fine merino or crossbred)\nWeave structure: Five-shaft satin twill, heavily milled and face-finished\nTypical weight: 340–500 g/m²\nSurface character: Smooth, close-cut dense nap, slight lustre\nSeason suitability: Autumn and winter formal wear',
