    seo_title: 'What is Madras? | William Ashford',
    seo_description: 'Madras is a lightweight handwoven cotton from South India, known for its vivid plaid checks and natural bleed. Discover its place in summer menswear.',
    short_definition: 'Madras is a fine, lightweight cotton fabric handwoven in the Chennai (formerly Madras) region of South India, characterised by its bright, multi-coloured plaid or check patterns and a pleasantly irregular texture. It is one of the classic summer fabrics of British and American warm-weather dressing.',
    full_definition: `Madras cloth takes its name from the city of Madras — now Chennai — on the south-eastern coast of India, where a tradition of handwoven, brightly dyed cotton cloth has existed for many centuries. The fabric first entered European fashion during the colonial period, when British traders and administrators returned from India with lengths of vividly coloured cotton that could not be replicated by the more mechanically precise looms of the British textile industry. Its charm lay precisely in its difference: the slight irregularities of the handwoven cloth, the vivid vegetable and later chemical dyes, and the distinctive multi-coloured plaids and checks that distinguished it from any domestic equivalent.

Authentic madras is woven on handlooms from fine, combed cotton yarn. The pattern is set in the warp before weaving begins, with the weft threads then adding additional colour sequences to create a plaid — a pattern in which both horizontal and vertical stripes of different colours intersect. Unlike the strict mathematical repetition of tartan, madras plaids are often less symmetrical and more exuberant, with colours placed with a more instinctive hand. The result is a cloth of considerable visual energy and warmth.

One of the defining characteristics of genuine madras is "bleed" — the tendency of the natural or partially fixed dyes to migrate slightly into adjacent colour areas when the cloth is washed. Rather than being considered a defect, this bleed is prized as a mark of authenticity and is responsible for the soft, almost watercolour quality that genuine madras acquires with age and washing. A madras shirt that has been washed many times has a beauty quite different from its original state: the colours soften and blend, the hand becomes more supple, and the cloth takes on a faded, lived-in quality that is entirely appropriate to its casual summer character.

In British menswear, madras is associated above all with summer informality — the sailing holiday, the cricket weekend, the long garden lunch. It is used most commonly in shirts, shorts, and unlined summer blazers and is best worn when the occasion calls for ease and colour rather than formality. A well-chosen madras jacket or shirt is one of the most characterful and personal things a man can wear in the summer months.`,
    properties: 'Fibre type: Cotton (traditionally handwoven, fine combed yarn)\nWeave structure: Plain weave plaid, handwoven with intentional irregularity\nTypical weight: 100–160 g/m²\nColour character: Vivid multi-coloured plaids; natural bleed with washing\nSeason suitability: Spring and summer',
    care_tips: 'Machine wash on a gentle cool cycle; expect some colour bleed in early washes — this is normal and desirable\nWash separately for the first two or three washes to avoid transferring dye to other garments\nLine dry in indirect light — strong sunlight accelerates the natural fading that gives madras its aged beauty\nIron at a medium cotton setting while slightly damp for a crisp finish\nDo not dry clean — the chemical solvents can strip the natural dye quality that makes madras distinctive',
