    term_name: 'Suit Interlining',
    seo_title: 'What is Suit Interlining? | William Ashford',
    seo_description: 'Suit interlining is the hidden layer that gives a jacket its shape. Learn the differences between fused, half-canvas, and full-canvas suit construction.',
    short_definition: 'Suit interlining — often called canvas — refers to the internal structural layer or layers built into the chest and front of a tailored jacket to give it its shape, support the outer cloth, and allow the lapels and chest to roll and conform naturally to the wearer\'s body. It is one of the most important elements distinguishing fine tailoring from mass-produced suiting.',
    full_definition: `The interlining of a suit jacket is invisible to the casual observer, yet it is arguably the single most important determinant of how a suit looks, moves, and wears over its lifetime. A jacket without proper interlining is merely cloth stitched into shape; a jacket with a well-constructed interlining has life, structure, and an ability to conform to the wearer's body that cannot be achieved by the outer cloth alone.

Traditional suit canvas — the dominant form of interlining in fine tailoring for centuries — is made from a combination of materials, typically including a horsehair canvas (woven from a blend of natural horsehair and wool or cotton), a domette or bump interlining for padding, and occasionally a felt or linen layer. These layers are hand-stitched together and to the outer cloth using a technique called pad-stitching, in which thousands of small, diagonal stitches attach the canvas to the chest piece of the jacket without being visible on the outside. This process — the most labour-intensive element of bespoke tailoring — takes many hours per jacket and is what gives a full-canvas suit its characteristic soft roll of lapel, its chest that moulds gradually to the wearer's form, and its ability to recover its shape after wearing.

There are three main types of suit construction distinguished by their approach to interlining. Full-canvas construction, as described above, uses a canvas layer that runs the full length of the jacket front, entirely hand-stitched to the cloth. This is the construction of bespoke and the finest ready-to-wear tailoring. Half-canvas construction uses a hand-stitched canvas in the chest and lapel area — approximately the upper half of the jacket front — while the lower half uses a lighter fusible or sewn interlining. This represents an excellent balance of quality and cost in the upper tier of ready-to-wear. Fused or bonded construction dispenses with canvas entirely, using instead a heat-bonded interfacing glued directly to the outer cloth by machine. This produces a jacket that is initially crisp and structured but which tends to delaminate — develop bubbling between the cloth and the fusing — after repeated cleaning, and which never acquires the natural moulding of a canvassed garment.

The choice of interlining has direct consequences for how a jacket wears over its lifetime. A full- or half-canvas jacket improves with wearing and cleaning; the canvas softens and moulds to the body, and the lapels develop a roll that is uniquely the wearer's. A fused jacket, no matter how good the cloth, cannot achieve this and will visibly deteriorate with time.`,
    properties: 'Construction types: Full canvas, half canvas, fused/bonded\nTraditional canvas materials: Horsehair canvas, linen, domette, felt\nAttachment method (canvas): Hand pad-stitching (bespoke/high RTW)\nAttachment method (fused): Machine heat-bonding\nLongevity: Full canvas outlasts fused by many years; improves with wear',
    care_tips: 'Dry clean canvassed jackets with a specialist who understands tailored construction — aggressive cleaning can disturb the canvas layers\nAlways hang a suit jacket on a broad, shaped wooden hanger to allow the canvas and cloth to recover their form after wearing\nAvoid prolonged steaming directly onto the chest piece, which can temporarily distort the canvas; use light steaming at a distance\nFor fused jackets, avoid high-heat pressing which accelerates delamination — use a pressing cloth and low heat\nAllow at least 24 hours between wearings so the interlining can fully recover from the compression of a day\'s use',
